benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: PUT /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/paymentMethods/{paymentMethodId}/setDefault - Set the default payment method

covered: PUT Valid Request: Scenarios TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04 confirm successful updates with required and optional parameters.

Error Handling: TC06 (invalid accountId format), TC07 (invalid paymentMethodId format), TC08 (non-existent accountId), TC09 (non-existent paymentMethodId), TC10 (paymentMethodId not belonging to account), TC11 (missing required header), TC12 (unauthorized user), TC13 (service unavailable), TC19 (injection attempts with header), TC23 (invalid UUIDs partially), TC21 (account with no payment methods results in 404 for default), TC16 (boundary UUIDs)
gaps: Partial Update: No test explicitly asserting that PUT requires full replacement and rejects partial updates if applicable.
Authorization: While TC12 covers unauthorized user, explicit tests for 403 Forbidden on insufficient privileges could be considered (depending on auth model).
Rate Limiting: No tests for handling multiple rapid PUT requests or throttling behavior.
Caching Behavior: No tests around caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) for this PUT operation.
Pagination: Not applicable for a single-resource PUT, but guideline mentions GET/Pagination scenarios; no explicit pagination tests exist (not expected for PUT).
Performance under load: Some performance aspects are implied (TC17/TC22), but no explicit SLA/timeout tests for long-running unpaid-invoice processing beyond general expectations.
recommendations: Add a test to verify that the API rejects partial updates or unrelated payload changes when PUT semantics require full replacement (to align with Partial Update guideline).
Include an explicit authorization/permission test to cover a 403 scenario if your system differentiates between unauthenticated (401) and unauthorized (403) users.
Add rate-limiting/throttling tests to ensure the system handles bursts of PUT requests without degraded behavior (e.g., 429 or appropriate error handling).
Add caching-related tests for this PUT (even if optional), e.g., verify absence/presence of ETag or Cache-Control headers when applicable.
Consider a focused performance test under concurrent load (enhance TC22) with measurable SLA targets to validate response times under stress.
